# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

## Critical Breaking Changes

| Issue | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `ThreadAbortException` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Wakes blocking calls | Still works, but discouraged |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue` | Manual synchronization | Use `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>` |

## Race Condition in Original Code

The original has a bug: if multiple items are enqueued before `RunLoop` processes, `_newEvent.Set()` coalesces signals but only **one** `Dequeue` runs per `WaitOne` cycle — remaining items stall until the next enqueue.

## Migrated Code (Modern .NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Clean shutdown — expected
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _processingTask is null) return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete();           // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        try
        {
            await _processingTask;            // wait for drain or cancellation
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // Your processing logic here
    }
}
```

## Key Migration Decisions

**1. `Channel<T>` replaces `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock`**
- Thread-safe, backpressure-aware, zero manual synchronization
- `ReadAllAsync` drains *all* queued items — fixes the coalescing bug

**2. `CancellationToken` replaces `Thread.Abort()`/`Interrupt()`**
- Cooperative cancellation is the only supported model in .NET 8
- `Thread.Abort()` will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime

**3. `Task.Run` replaces `new Thread(...).Start()`**
- Uses the thread pool; avoids dedicating an OS thread to mostly-idle work
- If `Handle()` is CPU-bound and long-running, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`

**4. Graceful then forced shutdown**
- `Writer.Complete()` lets in-flight items drain
- `CancelAfter` acts as the hard timeout (replaces `Join` + `Abort`)

## If You Need Synchronous API Compatibility

```csharp
// Drop-in wrapper if callers can't use async
public void Stop()
{
    StopAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5))
        .AsTask()
        .GetAwaiter()
        .GetResult();
}
```

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---|---|
| Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` broadly | Only catch `when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid hiding bugs |
| Forgetting `Writer.Complete()` | Without it, `ReadAllAsync` never terminates — your stop hangs |
| Using `BlockingCollection<T>` instead | Works, but blocks a thread; `Channel<T>` is the modern async primitive |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks kernel handles; implement `IAsyncDisposable` |
| Calling `.Result`/`.Wait()` on the processing task | Deadlocks in UI/ASP.NET sync contexts; use `await` or `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` |
